<br>
There's fair use to consider and I think some allowance for derivative works.<br>
<br>
The key point here is when an artist says don't do something with their work and you....<br>
<br>
... do what they asked not to do<br>
... claim you paid them so it's okay<br>
... ignore (and in fact edit content and repost) a request by the artist to stop using they're material<br>
<br>
... you're not going to be getting on their good side.<br>
<br>
Who knows, might have been an entirely different result if you'd asked for permission in the first place.  It's perfectly within the copyright holder's rights to grant you limited rights to their material.  Often, that's something you'll get in exchange for making a donation, although not something you're entitled to.  It's also not something you're likely to get if you start off by ignoring them or treating them like you own their hard work.<br>
<br>
The whole internet makes it a bit more difficult to deal with, but theoretically, EQPA could contact EZBoard and Hayley's ISP to get the information required to bring a RL case against him/her/it, although the odds of any money being involved is slim and it probably isn't worth the time, unless they're bored and want to make an example of somebody. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=5948">Duke Krazaak Crushbone</a> &lt<a href="http://www.hneguild.com">Heaven and Earth</a>&gt<BR>
